Just as the woebegone 118th Congress seems incapable of ending without a ba=
ng, amid an already combustible lame duck session ahead of Donald Trump=E2=
=80=99s return, a leadership battle over the House Agriculture Committee is=
 quickly becoming Capitol Hill=E2=80=99s hottest schoolyard brawl. Democrat=
s, still kicking themselves for not deposing an 82-year-old Joe Biden earli=
er in the cycle, are now fiercely debating how to re-energize their ranks w=
ith young blood. And the results have spilled out into public view.

Two longtime House committee leaders, Ra=C3=BAl Grijalva (76) and Jerry Nad=
ler (77), have already capitulated to more youthful challengers on Natural =
Resources and Judiciary, respectively. Among the last vulnerable ranking me=
mbers still holding down their post is David Scott (79), a veteran of the A=
g Committee, who
faces serious threats on two fronts this month=E2=80=94from California=E2=
=80=99s Jim Costa (72) and Minnesota third-termer Angie Craig (52). But the=
re=E2=80=99s a clear push underway to elevate Craig, a moderate swing-distr=
ict member who=E2=80=99s portraying herself as a breath of fresh air. Shoul=
d she prevail, it would represent a generational earthquake, making Craig o=
ne of the youngest Democratic committee ranking members in recent memory.

The mutiny started, naturally, via one of the House=E2=80=99s most somnolen=
t, and typically least-controversial chores: reauthorizing the Farm Bill. I=
t=E2=80=99s a bipartisan behemoth that has to pass every five to seven year=
s, and is thus laden with goodies for both sides: agriculture industry subs=
idies required by Republicans and SNAP food assistance money (formerly know=
n as food stamps) favored by Democrats. But Congress couldn=E2=80=99t muste=
r the legislative muscle to replace the bill that expired last year, and no=
w a fight has broken out over which
Democrat will lead the party on the committee.

Ag, of course, is not normally where the hot action takes place. It=E2=80=
=99s one of those committee assignments that members dutifully accept as an=
 obligation during their first or second terms, en route to bigger and bett=
er committees like Appropriations or Energy and Commerce. That is, except i=
n a Farm Bill Year, when the old bill expires and a new one (or an extensio=
n) has to pass, with all those extra treats to be had. That=E2=80=99s when =
everyone wants to be on Ag=E2=80=94the nerve center of influence for steeri=
ng some $700 million worth of taxpayer money.

