/i>: What kind of impact do you think Biden=E2=80=99s pardon of his son Hun=
ter will have on his legacy? And what do you think of Biden=E2=80=99s presi=
dential legacy in general?</b><br/><br/><i>Chris Cillizza</i>: Biden, of co=
urse, had to know at some level that this was going to affect his legacy, a=
nd not in a positive way. I do think the pardon impacts that, because of th=
e way he got elected president after two failed attempts, saying that he wa=
s going to restore dignity, honor, and respect to the White House after <b>=
Donald Trump</b> desecrated it. And by and large, he did that. The problem =
is that one of the last things, if not <i>the </i>last thing he does as pre=
sident, is pardon his son in this broad and expansive way that he said he w=
ouldn=E2=80=99t do. <br/><br/>Even though we suffer a little bit from recen=
cy bias, I think the sweeping
nature of it, and the fact that he repeatedly said he wouldn=E2=80=99t do i=
t, and the fact that he said he was going to be better, all combined into a=
 sort of toxic legacy stew for him=E2=80=A6 The last year and a half, to me=
, have been very selfish. The decision to run again was a gigantic politica=
l mistake. Getting out of the race as late as he did, and then pardoning hi=
s son, are going to tarnish his political legacy and probably overshadow hi=
s legislative legacy. <br/></td>
