          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Just as the woebego=
ne 118th Congress seems incapable of ending without a bang, amid an already=
 combustible lame duck session ahead of <b>Donald Trump</b>=E2=80=99s retur=
n, a leadership battle over the House Agriculture Committee is quickly beco=
ming Capitol Hill=E2=80=99s hottest schoolyard brawl. Democrats, still kick=
ing themselves for not deposing an 82-year-old <b>Joe Biden</b> earlier in =
the cycle, are now fiercely debating how to re-energize their ranks with yo=
ung blood. And the results have spilled out into public view.<br/><br/>Two =
longtime House committee leaders, <b>Ra=C3=BAl Grijalva </b>(76) and <b>Jer=
ry Nadler </b>(77), have already capitulated to more youthful challengers o=
n Natural Resources and Judiciary, respectively. Among the last vulnerable =
ranking members still holding down their post is <b>David Scott </b>(79), a=
 veteran of the Ag Committee, who
faces serious threats on two fronts this month=E2=80=94from California=E2=
=80=99s <b>Jim Costa</b> (72) and Minnesota third-termer <b>Angie Craig </b=
>(52). But there=E2=80=99s a clear push underway to elevate Craig, a modera=
te swing-district member who=E2=80=99s portraying herself as a breath of fr=
esh air. Should she prevail, it would represent a generational earthquake, =
making Craig one of the youngest Democratic committee ranking members in re=
cent memory. <br/><br/>The mutiny started, naturally, via one of the House=
=E2=80=99s most somnolent, and typically least-controversial chores: reauth=
orizing the Farm Bill. It=E2=80=99s a bipartisan behemoth that has to pass =
every five to seven years, and is thus laden with goodies for both sides: a=
griculture industry subsidies required by Republicans and SNAP food assista=
nce money (formerly known as food stamps) favored by Democrats. But Congres=
s couldn=E2=80=99t muster the legislative muscle to replace the bill that e=
xpired last year, and now a fight has broken out over which
Democrat will lead the party on the committee. <br/><br/>Ag, of course, is =
not normally where the hot action takes place. It=E2=80=99s one of those co=
mmittee assignments that members dutifully accept as an obligation during t=
heir first or second terms, en route to bigger and better committees like A=
ppropriations or Energy and Commerce. That is, except in a <i>Farm Bill Yea=
r</i>, when the old bill expires and a new one (or an extension) has to pas=
s, with all those extra treats to be had. That=E2=80=99s when <i>everyone</=
i> wants to be on Ag=E2=80=94the nerve center of influence for steering som=
e $700 million worth of taxpayer money. <br/></td>
